<head>
<title>Binomial Formulas</title>
</head>
<body>
<p>For those who are interested, these formulas may be derived with the aid of the rule for variance
            of a sum of random variables. We think of our binomial X with n and p as the sum of n
            identical "Bernoulli" random variables X1 through Xn, each representing one of the n
            trials. Each of the Xi has just two possibilities: success (X<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T215946-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T215946-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>1, with probability p), or failure (X<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T215949-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T215950-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>0, with probability 1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T215955-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>-<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T215955-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>p), as shown in the probability distribution table below.</p>
<!--:WARNING: Removed paragraph enclosing image element.--><image style="block" src="../../_m3_random_variables/webcontent/image097.gif"
    alt="A table with two columns, labeled &quot;X_i&quot; and &quot;Probability.&quot; Here are the
    two rows of the table:
            0: 1-p;
            1: p;"/>
<p>The mean of each Xi is 0(1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220006-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>-<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220006-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>p)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220007-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>+<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220008-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>1(p)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220011-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220011-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>p<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220027-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            and the variance is</p>
<!--:WARNING: Removed paragraph enclosing image element.--><image style="block" src="../../_m3_random_variables/webcontent/image098.gif"
        alt="&sigma;_i&sup;2 = (0-p)&sup2;&times;(1-p) + (1-p)&sup2;&times;p = p(1-p)[p+(1-p)] = p(1-p)"/>
<p>Because variance is additive, if we sum up n such random variables to form the binomial random
            variable X<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220042-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220042-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>X1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220043-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>+<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220044-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>...<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220045-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>+<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220045-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>Xn, its variance will be the sum of n variances p(1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220051-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>-<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220051-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>p), or np(1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220053-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>-<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T220053-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>p).</p>
